{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_curry_ver02/data/sn92073229/00332891893/1949060301/0529.xml":{"full_text":"Friday, June 3,1949\nGraham Says Current Revenues Will Provide\nAdequate Road-Building Fund, So State Does\nNot Need Bond Issue Proposed by Gov. Scott\nA. H. Graham of Hillsboro,\nformer chairman of the State\nHighway Commission, issued\nMonday a statement in which\nhe reiterated his opposition to\nGovernor Scott\u2019s proposal that\nthe State borrow, through a bond\nissue, $200,000,000 for rural\nroad-building.\nHe expressed the opinion that,\nprovided there should be no\nserious business depression, the\npresent State administration\nwould have, out of current reve\nnues, approximately $260,000,-\n000 for road work, and that on\nthe basis of the amount spent\nfor construction and mainten\nance in the last administration\n($191,000,000), the State would\nhave about $70,000,000 more\nthan was available during the\nCherry administration.\n\u201cIt is my considered opinion,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Graham, \u201cthat by the\nend of this fiscal year, on June\nHO, the Highway Commission\nwill have a surplus of between\n26 and 30 millions of dollars and\nI believe the surplus will be\nnearer 30 than 25 million.\n\u201cI shall cast my vote for the\nschool building bonds in Satur\nday\u2019s election, but I think it is\nunfair for proponents of the\nroad bonds to tie their little red\nwagon to the school bonds.\nOnet-fl-y\u00abar^-\nPRICK\nH^Ai/nA\nDIOOORANT\nfIOULARIY *l\u00b0\u00b0\n50 PLUS TAX\n\\JimPLP IIMI TI 0\nONIY\nSO EXCEPTIONALLY GOOD that onee you try Dorothy\nPerkins flower-fresh Deodorant you prefer It always! Try it\ntoday FOR CHARMS SAKE: It\u2019s effective andgenriy safe,\never-fragrant, ever-creamy. Today it\u2019s AN EXCEPTIONAL\nBUY, too, so get your family summer supply now during this\nhalf-price sale!\nANDREWS-HENNINGER CO.\nChapel Hill, N. C.\nKIDDY-KAR WRECK\nIF some one is injured while on your prem\n-1 ises, will you be able financially to pay for\nany damages awarded against you? Will\nyou be provided with a legal defense?\nYou can be protected against such loss by\nComprehensive Personal Liability Insur\nance.\nAsk this agency about it.\nService Insurance Realty Co.\nPhone P-419\nInsurance, Property Management, Real Estate\nCollier Cobb, Jr., President\nClyde E. Someday, WHfrad L. Breaker, Jr,\nMgr, Real Rotate Dept. toewaaee Be*.\n\u201cAfter necessary deductions\nfor administrative expense, debt\nservice on bond issues floated\nfor road purposes from 1921 to\n1931, and other expenses borne\nby the State highway fund, ap\nproximately $191,000,000 was\nspent during the Cherry admin\nistration for construction and\nmaintenance of the State\u2019s pri\nmary and secondary roads, with\nemphasis being placed on the\npaving and improving of second\nary roads. During the calendar\nyear 1948 3,356 miles bf roads\nwere paved and of these 2,524\nmiles were rural roads.\u201d\nProvided there is no \u201cserious\nbusiness recession\u201d Graham\npredicted the present adminis\ntration will have approximately\n$260,000,000 available for actual\nroad work after necessary de\nductions are made for adminis\ntrative, debt service and other\nitems, or \u201cjust about $70,000,-\n00(f more than was available for\nactual road work during the\nCherry administration.\u201d\n\u201cIt must not be forgotten that\nthe Highway Commission is now\nenjoying the largest amount of\ncurrent revenue ever received.\nThe plan to issue $200,000,000\nin bonds is a most brazen grab\nto divert public funds to the\nbenefit of one group at the ex-\nTHE CHAPEL HILL WEEKLY\npense of all other groups in the\nState. If the entire credit of the\nState covering road and high\nway financing is dissipated at\nthis time, our primary highway\nsystem will be in a sad state long\nbefore these bonds are retired.\n\u201cAccording to the latest avail\nable information, 21 states are\nfree of road bond indebtedness,\nsix others have an indebtedness\nof less than $10,000,000,- and\nonly two states\u2014Arkansas and\nLouisiana-!\u2014have a road bond in\ndebtedness in excess of $50,-\n000,000.\n\u201cIf the highway policy pro\nposed by the present State ad\nministration should be approved\nby the voters in next Saturday\u2019s\nelection, North Carolina will\nmove from a practically debt\nfree State with a large cash sur\nplus to the most unenviable po\nsition of being the first state in\nthe nation in road bond indebt\nedness and will rank third in\nthe nation in total indebtedness,\nbeing exceeded only by New\nYork and Illinois.\u201d\nIt's Smart to Shop m\nChapel Hill\nTODAY\nSsf\nWwBHMP IBMWiw mr Hi\nSATURDAY\nRochelle Hudson\nCesar Romero\nin\n\u201cSHOW THEM NO MERCY\u201d\nsunday-monday\u201d\nI\nl\"ft.WK\u00bb Cin I\nPrOIBT\nI m eiiuii bumu vmiai\nL\u2014\nTUESDAY\nlat.d upon Ih* c lllip I\nW// \u201cWondi. Ct.ol.d by Ow \u00bb\u00abv\u00bb\u00bb\nWEDNESDAY\nTHURSDAY\nVillagers Get Athletic Awards\nThe following Chapel Hillians were\namong the University athletes who\nreceived awards at the annual Awards\nNight program last week: Charles S.\nBartlett, Jr., and Samuel R. Mc-\nCauley, varsity swimming; Lawrence\nCheek, freshman basketball; and Jack\nCohen and E. Carrington Smith, Jr.,\nfreshman swimming. The awards were\npresented by R. A. Fetzer, director\nof athletics.\nGrape Juice 19c\nTuna Fish -39 c\nlona 10 lbs. 49c f\nPeas 3 Cars 29c f Sunkist Lemons i I\nAdcP Grapefruit DOZ. 49C\nc n<ki 17- Watermelons i\nSections -17 c Lb. 4y 2 c\nPerfect Strike Chum Green Tender\nSalmon 45c st 8\nSouthern St,L* 2,b 25C\nVanilla Wales- Iff 23c i Larg VKf uce f\nUhb,-. Tometo Fresh Tender Corn\nJuice -29 c 6 Ears 33c J>\nGreen Top Carrots\nSuper Right Meats 2 for 17c\nDressed and Drawn Fryers lb. 47c Winesap Apples 1\nBoned and Rolled Chuck Roast lb. 59c 2 lbs. 39c\nSirloin Steak lb. 79e Yellow Squash 1\nFresh Ground Beef lb. 49c 1 2 lbs. 17c J t\nShort Ribs Beef lb. 29c 1 n n y* -f'n V\"\nVeal Shoulder Chops lb. 49c uen Maid Uncoiomd